<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-326-374  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 326 374.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>The Journal of Systems and Software  Nov 1990 v13 n3 p231(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Improving software project management.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Pulk, Brian E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>While the complexity of software-based products has increasedenormously over the past decade, the increased cost of softwaredevelopment goes far beyond that which can be explained by thisincreased complexity.andP;  The single most glaring cause of this costincrease is the lack of effective leadership within softwaredevelopment projects.andP;  This lack of leadership is due to anineffective university educational system for software engineers,poor planning and estimation of software projects, and adivergence between software and product development technologies.andO;In today's software development environment, researchers,academics, engineers, and managers are focusing more and moreenergy toward developing software engineering as a science inorder to deal with the increasing complexity of softwareapplications.andP;  In so doing, there is a trend toward losing sightof the product, application, and technology for which the softwareis being developed, thus creating a gap between software andproduct development.andP;  This trend is a primary cause of increasingsoftware development costs and the bridging of the gap requireseffective leadership and project management within the softwaredesign teams.andP;  (Reprinted by permission of the publisher)andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Program Development TechniquesSoftware DesignSoftware EngineeringProject Management.andO;Feature:   illustrationgraph.andO;Caption:   Development effort vs. calendar time. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>